---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
const title = "power basics — ecute.club";
---
<BaseLayout {title}>
  <article class="container">
    <h1>power basics</h1>
    <p>power keeps everything alive. we care about <strong>voltage</strong> (how hard it pushes), <strong>current</strong> (how much flows), and <strong>polarity</strong> (which side is +).</p>

    <h2>what is a power supply?</h2>
    <p>a source that provides a (mostly) steady voltage and enough current. examples: batteries, USB ports, bench supplies, or a regulator fed by a higher voltage.</p>

    <h2>core ideas</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>voltage (V):</strong> parts are rated to run at specific voltages (e.g., 3.3 V, 5 V, 12 V).</li>
      <li><strong>current (A):</strong> how much the load draws. a supply should be rated for <em>at least</em> that much.</li>
      <li><strong>power (W) = V×I:</strong> tells you heat/wasting limits in regulators and resistors.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>regulators</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>LDO</strong> (linear): simple; needs headroom; drops extra voltage as heat.</li>
      <li><strong>buck</strong> (switching): efficient; uses an inductor; a bit noisier but cooler.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="diagram" role="img" aria-label="battery → regulator → 5V rail with decoupling">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 560 160" width="100%" height="auto">
        <rect x="0" y="0" width="560" height="160" rx="16" fill="var(--card)"/>
        <text x="36" y="84" class="mono">battery</text>
        <rect x="30" y="60" width="50" height="40" rx="6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/>
        <line x1="80" y1="80" x2="200" y2="80" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/>
        <rect x="200" y="62" width="80" height="36" rx="8" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/>
        <text x="240" y="84" class="mono" text-anchor="middle">reg</text>
        <line x1="280" y1="80" x2="420" y2="80" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/>
        <text x="430" y="84" class="mono">+5V</text>
        <line x1="340" y1="80" x2="340" y2="110" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/>
        <rect x="330" y="110" width="20" height="20" rx="3" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/>
        <line x1="340" y1="130" x2="340" y2="150" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/>
        <line x1="40" y1="150" x2="520" y2="150" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/>
        <text x="18" y="154" class="mono">0V</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <h2>little rules</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>mind <strong>polarity</strong> (mark + and 0 V); add reverse-protection (Schottky or “ideal diode” MOSFET).</li>
      <li>decouple every IC: <strong>0.1 µF</strong> by the pins + one <strong>10–47 µF</strong> per rail section.</li>
      <li>size traces/wires for current; if warm, they’re too small.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
